[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:aws-x-ray/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In computer science, a **call stack** is a stack data structure that stores information about the active subroutines and inline blocks of a computer program.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This type of stack is also known as an **execution stack**, **program stack**, **control stack**, **run-time stack**, or **machine stack**, and is often shortened to simply the "**stack**".
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Although maintenance of the call stack is important for the proper functioning of most software, the details are normally hidden and automatic in high-level programming languages.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Many computer instruction sets provide special instructions for manipulating stacks.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] A call stack is used for several related purposes, but the main reason for having one is to keep track of the point to which each active subroutine should return control when it finishes executing.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] An active subroutine is one that has been called, but is yet to complete execution, after which control should be handed back to the point of call.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Such activations of subroutines may be nested to any level (recursive as a special case), hence the stack structure.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine `DrawSquare` calls a subroutine `DrawLine` from four different places, `DrawLine` must know where to return when its execution completes.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] To accomplish this, the address following the instruction that jumps to `DrawLine`, the *return address*, is pushed onto the top of the call stack as part of each call.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] If a called subroutine calls on yet another subroutine, it will push another return address onto the call stack, and so on, with the information stacking up and unstacking as the program dictates.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] If the pushing consumes all of the space allocated for the call stack, an error called a stack overflow occurs, generally causing the program to crash.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Adding a block's or subroutine's entry to the call stack is sometimes called "winding", and removing entries "unwinding".
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] There is usually exactly one call stack associated with a running program (or more accurately, with each task or thread of a process), although additional stacks may be created for signal handling or cooperative multitasking (as with setcontext).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Since there is only one in this important context, it can be referred to as *the* stack (implicitly "of the task"); however, in the Forth programming language the *data stack* or *parameter stack* is accessed more explicitly than the call stack and is commonly referred to as *the* stack (see below).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In high-level programming languages, the specifics of the call stack are usually hidden from the programmer.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] They are given access only to a set of functions, and not the memory on the stack itself.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Most assembly languages, on the other hand, require programmers to be involved in manipulating the stack.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The actual details of the stack in a programming language depend upon the compiler, operating system, and the available instruction set.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] As noted above, the primary purpose of a call stack is to *store the return addresses*.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When a subroutine is called, the location (address) of the instruction at which the calling routine can later resume must be saved somewhere.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Using a stack to save the return address has important advantages over some alternative calling conventions, such as saving the return address before the beginning of the called subroutine or in some other fixed location.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] One is that each task can have its own stack, and thus the subroutine can be thread-safe, that is, able to be active simultaneously for different tasks doing different things.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Another benefit is that by providing reentrancy, recursion is automatically supported.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When a function calls itself recursively, a return address needs to be stored for each activation of the function so that it can later be used to return from the function activation.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Stack structures provide this capability automatically.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] , the variables that are known only within the active subroutine and do not retain values after it returns.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] It is often convenient to allocate space for this use by simply moving the top of the stack by enough to provide the space.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Note that each separate activation of a subroutine gets its own separate space in the stack for locals.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] may allocate a stack frame for local variables.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] As with a call frame, the values are lost when the block exits.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] be supplied to them by the code which calls them, and it is not uncommon that space for these parameters may be laid out in the call stack.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] will be used to pass the values, but if there are more parameters than can be handled this way, memory space will be needed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The call stack works well as a place for these parameters, especially since each call to a subroutine, which will have differing values for parameters, will be given separate space on the call stack for those values.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Operands for arithmetic or logical operations are most often placed into registers and operated on there.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] , is called an evaluation stack, and may occupy space in the call stack.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] , which are allowed to access the context of their enclosing routines, i.e., the parameters and local variables within the scope of the outer routines.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Such static nesting can repeat (a function declared within a function declared within a function…).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The implementation must provide a means by which a called function at any given static nesting level can reference the enclosing frame at each enclosing nesting level.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] which is indexed to locate a desired frame.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The depth of a routine's lexical nesting is a known constant, so the size of a routine's display is fixed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Also, the number of containing scopes to traverse is known, the index into the display is also fixed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] implemented such a display in hardware which supported up to 32 levels of static nesting.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The display entries denoting containing scopes are obtained from the appropriate prefix of the caller's display.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] An inner routine which recurses creates separate call frames for each invocation.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In this case, all of the inner routine's static links point to the same outer routine context.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] , a block within a procedure may have its own local variables, allocated on block entry and freed on block exit.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Similarly, the block may have its own exception handlers, deactivated at block exit.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Beside the return address, in some environments there may be other machine or software states that need to be restored when a subroutine returns.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This might include things like privilege level, exception-handling information, arithmetic modes, and so on.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] If needed, this may be stored in the call stack just as the return address is.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The typical call stack is used for the return address, locals, and parameters (known as a *call frame*).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In some environments there may be more or fewer functions assigned to the call stack.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Some Forths also have a third stack for floating-point parameters.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] A call stack is composed of **stack frames** (also called *activation records* or *activation frames*).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] These are machine dependent and ABI-dependent data structures containing subroutine state information.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Each stack frame corresponds to an invocation of a subroutine that has not yet completed with a return.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The stack frame at the top of the stack is for the currently executing routine.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] For example, if a subroutine named `DrawLine` is currently running, having been called by a subroutine `DrawSquare`, the top part of the call stack might be laid out like in the adjacent picture.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] A diagram like this can be drawn in either direction as long as the placement of the top, and so direction of stack growth, is understood.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Architectures differ as to whether call stacks grow towards higher addresses or towards lower addresses, so the logic of any diagram is not dependent on this addressing choice by convention.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] While it is actively executing, with its frame at the stack top, a routine can access the information within its frame as needed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When stack frame sizes can differ, such as between different functions or between invocations of a particular function, popping a frame off the stack does not constitute a fixed decrement of the **stack pointer**.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] At function return, the stack pointer is instead restored to the **frame pointer**, the value of the stack pointer just before the function was called.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Each stack frame contains a frame pointer to the top of the frame immediately below.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The stack pointer is a mutable register shared between all invocations.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] A frame pointer of a given invocation of a function is a copy of the stack pointer as it was before the function was invoked.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The locations of all other fields in the frame can be defined relative either to the top of the frame, as negative offsets of the stack pointer, or relative to the top of the frame below, as positive offsets of the frame pointer.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The location of the frame pointer itself must inherently be defined as a negative offset of the stack pointer.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In most systems a stack frame has a field to contain the previous value of the frame pointer register, the value it had while the caller was executing.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] For example, the stack frame of `DrawLine` would have a memory location holding the frame pointer value that `DrawSquare` uses (not shown in the diagram above).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The value is saved upon entry to the subroutine.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Having such a field in a known location in the stack frame enables code to access each frame successively underneath the currently executing routine's frame, and also allows the routine to easily restore the frame pointer to the *caller's* frame, just before it returns.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Programming languages that support nested subroutines also have a field in the call frame that points to the stack frame of the *latest* activation of the procedure that most closely encapsulates the callee, i.e. the immediate *scope* of the callee.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This is called an *access link* or *static link* (as it keeps track of static nesting during dynamic and recursive calls) and provides the routine (as well as any other routines it may invoke) access to the local data of its encapsulating routines at every nesting level.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Some architectures, compilers, or optimization cases store one link for each enclosing level (not just the immediately enclosing), so that deeply nested routines that access shallow data do not have to traverse several links; this strategy is often called a "display".
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Access links can be optimized away when an inner function does not access any (non-constant) local data in the encapsulation, as is the case with pure functions communicating only via arguments and return values, for example.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] For some purposes, the stack frame of a subroutine and that of its caller can be considered to overlap, the overlap consisting of the area where the parameters are passed from the caller to the callee.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In some environments, the caller pushes each argument onto the stack, thus extending its stack frame, then invokes the callee.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In other environments, the caller has a preallocated area at the top of its stack frame to hold the arguments it supplies to other subroutines it calls.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This area is sometimes termed the *outgoing arguments area* or *callout area*.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Under this approach, the size of the area is calculated by the compiler to be the largest needed by any called subroutine.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Usually the call stack manipulation needed at the site of a call to a subroutine is minimal (which is good since there can be many call sites for each subroutine to be called).
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The values for the actual arguments are evaluated at the call site, since they are specific to the particular call, and either pushed onto the stack or placed into registers, as determined by the used calling convention.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The actual call instruction, such as "branch and link", is then typically executed to transfer control to the code of the target subroutine.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In the called subroutine, the first code executed is usually termed the subroutine prologue, since it does the necessary housekeeping before the code for the statements of the routine is begun.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Similarly, the current stack pointer and/or frame pointer values may be pushed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] If frame pointers are being used, the prologue will typically set the new value of the frame pointer register from the stack pointer.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Space on the stack for local variables can then be allocated by incrementally changing the stack pointer.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The Forth programming language allows explicit winding of the call stack (called there the "return stack").
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When a subroutine is ready to return, it executes an epilogue that undoes the steps of the prologue.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This will typically restore saved register values (such as the frame pointer value) from the stack frame, pop the entire stack frame off the stack by changing the stack pointer value, and finally branch to the instruction at the return address.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Under many calling conventions, the items popped off the stack by the epilogue include the original argument values, in which case there usually are no further stack manipulations that need to be done by the caller.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] With some calling conventions, however, it is the caller's responsibility to remove the arguments from the stack after the return.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Returning from the called function will pop the top frame off the stack, perhaps leaving a return value.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The more general act of popping one or more frames off the stack to resume execution elsewhere in the program is called **stack unwinding** and must be performed when non-local control structures are used, such as those used for exception handling.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] In this case, the stack frame of a function contains one or more entries specifying exception handlers.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When an exception is thrown, the stack is unwound until a handler is found that is prepared to handle (catch) the type of the thrown exception.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Some languages have other control structures that require general unwinding.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Pascal allows a global goto statement to transfer control out of a nested function and into a previously invoked outer function.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This operation requires the stack to be unwound, removing as many stack frames as necessary to restore the proper context to transfer control to the target statement within the enclosing outer function.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Similarly, C has the `setjmp` and `longjmp` functions that act as non-local gotos.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Common Lisp allows control of what happens when the stack is unwound by using the `unwind-protect` special operator.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] When applying a continuation, the stack is (logically) unwound and then rewound with the stack of the continuation.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This is not the only way to implement continuations; for example, using multiple, explicit stacks, application of a continuation can simply activate its stack and wind a value to be passed.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The Scheme programming language allows arbitrary thunks to be executed in specified points on "unwinding" or "rewinding" of the control stack when a continuation is invoked.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] The call stack can sometimes be inspected as the program is running.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Depending on how the program is written and compiled, the information on the stack can be used to determine intermediate values and function call traces.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This has been used to generate fine-grained automated tests, and in cases like Ruby and Smalltalk, to implement first-class continuations.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] As an example, the GNU Debugger (GDB) implements interactive inspection of the call stack of a running, but paused, C program.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Taking regular-time samples of the call stack can be useful in profiling the performance of programs as, if a subroutine's address appears in the call stack sampling data many times, it is likely to act as a code bottleneck and should be inspected for performance problems.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] One such attack involves filling one buffer with arbitrary executable code, and then overflowing this or some other buffer to overwrite some return address with a value that points directly to the executable code.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] As a result, when the function returns, the computer executes that code.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] This kind of an attack can be blocked with W^X, but similar attacks can succeed even with W^X protection enabled, including the return-to-libc attack or the attacks coming from return-oriented programming.
[src:aws-x-ray/call-stack] Various mitigations have been proposed, such as storing arrays in a completely separate location from the return stack, as is the case in the Forth programming language.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Micro-Services are composed using Unix-like pipelines (the Web meets Unix = true loose-coupling).
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Services can call services (+multiple language run-times).
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Complex service assemblies are abstracted behind simple URI interfaces.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Computer microservices can be implemented in different programming languages and might use different infrastructures.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Therefore, the most important technology choices are the way microservices communicate with each other (synchronous, asynchronous, UI integration) and the protocols used for the communication (e.g.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In a traditional system, most technology choices like the programming language impact the whole system.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] Therefore, the approach to choosing technologies is quite different.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The Eclipse Foundation has published a specification for developing microservices, Eclipse MicroProfile.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] In a service mesh, each service instance is paired with an instance of a reverse proxy server, called a service proxy, sidecar proxy, or sidecar.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The service instance and sidecar proxy share a container, and the containers are managed by a container orchestration tool such as Kubernetes, Docker Swarm, or DC/OS.
[src:aws-x-ray/microservices] The service proxies are responsible for communication with other service instances and can support capabilities such as service (instance) discovery, load balancing, authentication and authorization, secure communications, and others.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] The concept of observability was introduced by the Hungarian-American engineer Rudolf E.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] A dynamical system designed to estimate the state of a system from measurements of the outputs is called a *state observer* for that system, such as Kalman filters.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] Consider a physical system modeled in state-space representation.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] A system is said to be **observable** if, for every possible evolution of state and control vectors, the current state can be estimated using only the information from outputs (physically, this generally corresponds to information obtained by sensors).
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] In other words, one can determine the behavior of the entire system from the system's outputs.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] On the other hand, if the system is not observable, there are state trajectories that are not distinguishable by only measuring the outputs.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] For time-invariant linear systems in the state space representation, there are convenient tests to check whether a system is observable.
