[src:aws-x-ray/observability] Early criteria for observability in nonlinear dynamic systems were discovered by Griffith and Kumar, Kou, Elliot and Tarn, and Singh.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] There also exist an observability criteria for nonlinear time-varying systems.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] Observability may also be characterized for steady state systems (systems typically defined in terms of algebraic equations and inequalities), or more generally, for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] Just as observability criteria are used to predict the behavior of Kalman filters or other observers in the dynamic system case, observability criteria for sets in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ are used to predict the behavior of data reconciliation and other static estimators.
[src:aws-x-ray/observability] In the nonlinear case, observability can be characterized for individual variables, and also for local estimator behavior rather than just global behavior.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] As the connection between application success and business success continues to gain recognition, particularly in the mobile space, application performance engineering has taken on a preventive and perfective role within the software development life cycle.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] As such, the term is typically used to describe the processes, people and technologies required to effectively test non-functional requirements, ensure adherence to service levels and optimize application performance prior to deployment.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The term *performance engineering* encompasses more than just the software and supporting infrastructure, and as such the term performance engineering is preferable from a macro view.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Adherence to the non-functional requirements is also validated post-deployment by monitoring the production systems.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This is part of IT service management (see also ITIL).
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Performance engineering has become a separate discipline at a number of large corporations, with tasking separate but parallel to systems engineering.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] It is pervasive, involving people from multiple organizational units; but predominantly within the information technology organization.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Because this discipline is applied within multiple methodologies, the following activities will occur within differently specified phases.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] During the first, Conceptual phase of a program or project, critical business processes are identified.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Typically they are classified as critical based upon revenue value, cost savings, or other assigned business value.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This classification is done by the business unit, not the IT organization.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] High level risks that may impact system performance are identified and described at this time.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] An example might be known performance risks for a particular vendor system.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Finally, performance activities, roles and deliverables are identified for the Elaboration phase.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Activities and resource loading are incorporated into the Elaboration phase project plans.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] During this defining phase, the critical business processes are decomposed to critical use cases.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Probe cases will be decomposed further, as needed, to single page (screen) transitions.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] These are the use cases that will be subjected to script driven performance testing.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The type of requirements that relate to performance engineering are the non-functional requirements, or NFR.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] While a functional requirement relates to which business operations are to be performed, a performance related non-functional requirement will relate to how fast that business operation performs under defined circumstances.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Early in this phase a number of performance tool related activities are required.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The performance test team normally does not execute performance tests in the development environment, but rather in a specialized pre-deployment environment that is configured to be as close as possible to the planned production environment.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This team will execute performance testing against test cases, validating that the critical use cases conform to the specified non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The team will execute load testing against a normally expected (median) load as well as a peak load.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] They will often run stress tests that will identify the system bottlenecks.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The data gathered, and the analysis, will be fed back to the group that does performance tuning.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Where necessary, the system will be tuned to bring nonconforming tests into conformance with the non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] If performance engineering has been properly applied at each iteration and phase of the project to this point, hopefully this will be sufficient to enable the system to receive performance certification.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] However, if for some reason (perhaps proper performance engineering working practices were not applied) there are tests that cannot be tuned into compliance, then it will be necessary to return portions of the system to development for refactoring.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] In some cases the problem can be resolved with additional hardware, but adding more hardware leads quickly to diminishing returns.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] During this final phase the system is deployed to the production environment.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] A number of preparatory steps are required.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] In the operational domain (post production deployment) performance engineering focuses primarily within three areas: service level management, capacity management, and problem management.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] In the service level management area, performance engineering is concerned with service level agreements and the associated systems monitoring that serves to validate service level compliance, detect problems, and identify trends.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] For example, when real user monitoring is deployed it is possible to ensure that user transactions are being executed in conformance with specified non-functional requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Transaction response time is logged in a database such that queries and reports can be run against the data.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This permits trend analysis that can be useful for capacity management.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] When user transactions fall out of band, the events should generate alerts so that attention may be applied to the situation.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] For capacity management, performance engineering focuses on ensuring that the systems will remain within performance compliance.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This means executing trend analysis on historical monitoring generated data, such that the future time of non compliance is predictable.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] For example, if a system is showing a trend of slowing transaction processing (which might be due to growing data set sizes, or increasing numbers of concurrent users, or other factors) then at some point the system will no longer meet the criteria specified within the service level agreements.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Capacity management is charged with ensuring that additional capacity is added in advance of that point (additional CPUs, more memory, new database indexing, et cetera) so that the trend lines are reset and the system will remain within the specified performance range.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] Within the problem management domain, the performance engineering practices are focused on resolving the root cause of performance related problems.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] These typically involve system tuning, changing operating system or device parameters, or even refactoring the application software to resolve poor performance due to poor design or bad coding practices.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] To ensure that there is proper feedback validating that the system meets the NFR specified performance metrics, any major system needs a monitoring subsystem.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The planning, design, installation, configuration, and control of the monitoring subsystem are specified by an appropriately defined monitoring process.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] The trend analysis component of this cannot be undervalued.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This functionality, properly implemented, will enable predicting when a given application undergoing gradually increasing user loads and growing data sets will exceed the specified non functional performance requirements for a given use case.
[src:aws-x-ray/performance-engineering] This permits proper management budgeting, acquisition of, and deployment of the required resources to keep the system running within the parameters of the non functional performance requirements.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:aws-x-ray/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
